    "\n",
    "## 🚀 Week 1: Python OOP Fundamentals\n",
    "\n",
    "### Step 1.1: Understand Classes and Objects\n",
    "\n",
    "**What to do:**\n",
    "- Watch video: Classes and Objects in Python\n",
    "- Create a simple class yourself\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why:** ML models are Python classes - you need to understand this first\n",
    "\n",
    "**Resources:**\n",
    "- 📹 [Python OOP - Classes and Objects (15 min)](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=apACNr7DC_s)\n",
    "- 📖 [Real Python - OOP Basics](https://realpython.com/python3-object-oriented-programming/#classes-are-blueprints-for-objects)\n",
    "\n",
    "**Time:** 1-2 hours\n",
    "\n",
    "**Your Task:**\n",
    "```python\n",
    "# Create this class yourself (don't copy!)\n",
    class Book:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, title, author, pages):\n",
    "        self.title = title\n",
    "        self.author = author\n",
    "        self.pages = pages\n",
    "        self.current_page = 0\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def read(self, pages):\n",
    "        self.current_page += pages\n",
    "        return f\"Reading... now on page {self.current_page}\"\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def get_progress(self):\n",
    "        return (self.current_page / self.pages) * 100\n",
    "\n",
    "# Test it:\n",
    "my_book = Book(\"ML Guide\", \"You\", 300)\n",
    "print(my_book.read(20))\n",
    "print(f\"Progress: {my_book.get_progress():.1f}%\")\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "**✅ Check:** Can you create a Book object and call its methods? Move to next step!\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### Step 1.2: Learn `__init__` and `self`\n",
    "\n",
    "**What to do:**\n",
    "- Understand constructor (`__init__`)\n",
    "- Understand instance variables (`self.variable`)\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why:** Every ML model class needs `__init__` to store parameters\n",
    "\n",
    "**Resources:**\n",
    "- 📹 [Python __init__ Explained (10 min)](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EXZt5c60pl0)\n",
    "- 📖 [Understanding self in Python](https://realpython.com/python3-object-oriented-programming/#understanding-self)\n",
    "\n",
    "**Time:** 1 hour\n",
    "\n",
    "**Your Task:**\n",
    "```python\n",
    "# Create a DataStats class\n",
    class DataStats:\n",
    "    def __init__(self, data):\n",
    "        self.data = data\n",
    "        self.count = len(data)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def get_mean(self):\n",
    "        return sum(self.data) / self.count\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def get_min(self):\n",
    "        return min(self.data)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def get_max(self):\n",
    "        return max(self.data)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Test with your Uri data parcel sizes\n",
    "sizes = [100, 500, 1000, 2500, 10000]\n",
    "stats = DataStats(sizes)\n",
    "print(f\"Mean: {stats.get_mean()}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Min: {stats.get_min()}, Max: {stats.get_max()}\")\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "**✅ Check:** Can you explain what `self` does? Move to next step!\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "### Step 1.3: Methods vs Functions\n",
    "\n",
    "**What to do:**\n",
    "- Learn the difference between methods and functions\n",
    "- Practice creating multiple methods in one class\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why:** ML models have multiple methods (fit, predict, score, etc.)\n",
    "\n",
    "**Resources:**\n",
    "- 📹 [Python Methods (8 min)](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cj4y6EUlU-Y)\n",
    "\n",
    "**Time:** 45 minutes\n",
    "\n",
    "**Your Task:**\n",
    "```python\n",
    "# Create a SimpleCalculator class with multiple methods\n",
    class SimpleCalculator:\n",
    "    def __init__(self):\n",
    "        self.history = []\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def add(self, a, b):\n",
    "        result = a + b\n",
    "        self.history.append(f\"{a} + {b} = {result}\")\n",
    "        return result\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def multiply(self, a, b):\n",
    "        result = a * b\n",
    "        self.history.append(f\"{a} * {b} = {result}\")\n",
    "        return result\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def get_history(self):\n",
    "        return self.history\n",
    "\n",
    "# Test it\n",
    "calc = SimpleCalculator()\n",
    "print(calc.add(5, 3))\n",
    "print(calc.multiply(4, 2))\n",
    "print(calc.get_history())\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "**✅ Check:** Can you create 3+ methods in one class? Week 1 complete! 🎉\n",
